"Bouchard J.N., Yamasaki H.","Implication of nitric oxide in the heat-stress-induced cell death of the symbiotic alga Symbiodinium microadriaticum",2009,"Marine Biology","156","11",,"2209","2220",,,10.1007/s00227-009-1249-3,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-71349086617&partnerID=40&md5=0ef29a3122f83672f2a550aaa8a64e74","Faculty of Science, University of the Ryukyus, Nishihara, Okinawa 903-0213, Japan; National Oceanography Centre, University of Southampton, Waterfront Campus, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom","Bouchard, J.N., Faculty of Science, University of the Ryukyus, Nishihara, Okinawa 903-0213, Japan, National Oceanography Centre, University of Southampton, Waterfront Campus, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom; Yamasaki, H., Faculty of Science, University of the Ryukyus, Nishihara, Okinawa 903-0213, Japan","One of the major consequences of global warming is a rise in sea surface temperature which may affect the survival of marine organisms including phytoplankton. Here, we provide experimental evidence for heat-induced cell death in a symbiotic microalga. Shifting Symbiodinium microadriaticum from 27 to 32°C resulted in an increase in mortality, an increase in caspase 3-like activity, and an increase in nitric oxide (NO) production. The caspase-like activity was strongly correlated with the production of NO in thermally challenged microalgae. For this experiment, the application of Ac-DEVD-CHO, a mammalian caspase 3-specific inhibitor, partly prevented (by 65%) the increase in caspase-like activity. To verify the relationship between NO and the caspase-like activity, S. microadriaticum were subsequently incubated with 1. 0 mM of the following chemical NO donors: sodium nitroprusside (SNP), S-nitrosoglutathione (GSNO), S-nitroso-N-acetylpenicillamine (SNAP) and 3,3bis(Aminoethyl)-1-hydroxy-2-oxo-1-triazene (NOC-18). The supplementation of both SNP and NOC-18 caused a significant increase in caspase-like activity compared to the control treatment. Pre-treatment of the microalgae with the inhibitor Ac-DEVD-CHO before the supplementation of the different NO donors completely prevented the increase in caspase-like activity. These results suggest that NO could play a role in the induction of cell death in heat-stressed S. microadriaticum by mediating an increase in caspase-like activity. © 2009 Springer-Verlag.",,"global warming; heat shock; microalga; mortality; nitric oxide; phytoplankton; sea surface temperature; survival; symbiont; algae; Mammalia; Symbiodinium microadriaticum",,,,,,"Affenzeller, M.J., Darehshouri, A., Andosch, A., Lütz, C., Lütz-meindl, U., Salt stress-induced cell death in the unicellular green alga Micrasterias denticulata (2009) J Exp Bot, 60, pp. 939-954; Almeida, B., Buttner, S., Ohlmeier, S., Silva, A., Mesquita, A., Sampaio-marques, B., Osório, N.S., Ludovico, P., NO-mediated apoptosis in yeast (2007) J Cell Sci, 120, pp. 3279-3288; Berges, J.A., Falkowski, P.G., Physiological stress and cell death in marine phytoplankton: Induction of proteases in response to nitrogen or light limitation (1998) Limnol Oceanogr, 43, pp. 129-135; Berman-frank, I., Bidle, K.D., Haramaty, L., Falkowski, P.G., The demise of the marine cyanobacterium Trichodesmium spp., via an autocatalysed cell death pathway (2004) Limnol Oceanogr, 49, pp. 997-1005; Bidle, K.D., Bender, S.J., Iron starvation and culture age activate metacaspases and programmed cell death in the marine diatom Thalassiosira pseudonana (2008) Eukaryot Cell, 7, pp. 223-236; Bidle, K.D., Falkowski, P.G., Cell death in planktonic, photosynthetic microorganisms (2004) Nat Rev, 2, pp. 643-655; Bidle, K.D., Hamaraty, L., Barcelos e Ramos, J., Falkowski, P., Viral activation and recruitment of metacaspases in the unicellular coccolithophore, Emiliania huxleyi (2007) Proc Natl Acad Sci USA, 104, pp. 6049-6054; Bonneau, L., Ge, Y., Drury, G.E., Gallois, P., What happened to plant caspases? (2008) J Exp Bot, 59 (3), pp. 491-499. , doi: 10. 1093/jxb/erm352; Bouchard, J.N., Yamasaki, H., Heat stress stimulates nitric oxide production in Symbiodinium microadriaticum: A possible linkage between nitric oxide and the coral bleaching phenomenon (2008) Plant Cell Physiol, 49, pp. 641-652; Bozhkov, P.V., Suarez, M.F., Filonova, L.H., Daniel, G., Zamyatnin Jr., A.A., Rodriguez-nieto, S., Zhivotovsky, B., Smertenko, A., Cysteine protease mcII-Pa executes programmed cell death during plant embryogenesis (2005) Proc Natl Acad Sci USA, 102, pp. 14463-14468; Brüne, B., Nitric oxide: NO apoptosis or turning it ON (2003) Cell Death Differ, 10, pp. 864-869; Brussaard, C.P.D., Marie, D., Thyrhaug, R., Bratbak, G., Flow cytometric analysis of phytoplankton viability following viral infection (2001) Aquat Microb Ecol, 26, pp. 157-166; Buma, A.G., Zemmerlink, H.J., Sjollema, K., Gieskes, W.W.C., UVB radiation modifies protein and photosynthetic pigment content, volume and ultrastructure of marine diatoms (1996) Mar Ecol Prog Ser, 142, pp. 47-54; Chung, C.-C., Hwang, S.-P.L., Chang, J., Nitric oxide as a signalling factor to upregulate the death-specific protein in a marine diatom, Skeletonema costatum, during blockage of electron flow in photosynthesis (2008) Appl Env Microbiol, 74, pp. 6521-6527; Clarke, A., Desikan, R., Hurst, R.D., Hancock, J.T., Neill, S.J., NO way back: Nitric oxide and programmed cell death in Arabidopsis thaliana suspension cultures (2000) Plant J, 24, pp. 667-677; Coles, S.L., Brown, B.E., Coral bleaching-capacity for acclimatization and adaptation (2003) Adv Mar Biol, 46, pp. 183-223; Darehshouri, A., Affenzeller, M., Lütz-meindl, U., Cell death upon H2O2 induction in the unicellular green alga Micrasterias (2008) Plant Biol, 10, pp. 32-745; de Pinto, M.C., Tommasi, F., de Gara, L., Changes in the antioxidant systems as part of the signaling pathway responsible for the programmed cell death activated by nitric oxide and reactive oxygen species in tobacco bright-yellow 2 